        {
            "type": "richtext",
            "title": "Val Bavona at a Glance",
            "titlelevel": 2,
            "text": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": "Bavona Valley, the steepest and rockiest valley in the Alps, is a dramatic testament to the power of glaciers. The rocky mountainsides rise hundreds of meters, revealing a landscape left behind by ancient ice flows. At its furthest point lies the "
                },
                {
                    "type": "link",
                    "url":"https://www.ticino.ch/en/commons/details/Bas%C3%B2dino-Glacier-/142499.html",
                    "target": "_blank",
                    "value": "Basòdino Glacier"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": ", a striking reminder of the valley’s glacial past."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "richtext",
            "text": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": "For centuries, humans have worked tirelessly to transform this wild terrain into habitable space. Meadows and fields have been painstakingly created between massive boulders and cliffs, reflecting a remarkable coexistence with nature. Even today, the valley retains its untamed character, offering visitors a glimpse into its natural and cultural richness."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "richtext",
            "text": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": "One unique aspect of Bavona Valley is its lack of an electricity network. Solar power fulfills the energy needs of its inhabitants, despite the valley’s own hydroelectric plants generating significant electricity. This self-reliance underscores the valley’s harmony with nature."
                }
            ]
        },
